I spoke again with Ely Goldin of Egorov, Puginsky, Afanasiev & Marks, who
represent Base Metals.  I told him we have paid for the material and have=
=20
clean
bills of lading.  He said they weren't looking to "jam anybody up" and woul=
d=20
try
to resolve the situation upon receipt of our paperwork (which I have just
received from Keith Whitehead) indicating our payment for the material and =
our
rightful ownership of same.

Unless this matter is otherwise resolved, their intention is to let the ves=
sel
continue discharging and seize the material thereafter.
Rukert Terminals advised me that a U.S. Marshall and two lawyers have alrea=
dy
been onboard the vessel and have confirmed this.  Discharge is continuing w=
ith
our cargo expected to be completed by next Wednesday.  I've conferred with =
our
lawyer, Arthur Taylor, and will fax the documents to Goldin this afternoon,=
=20
who
will look them over and get back to me tomorrow.

Regards,
Bob Klide



